# VII. Model generation
#We use randon forest to see which variables are more significant for the dataset.
set.seed(123)
rf<-randomForest(charges~smoker+age+bmi+children+region+male,data,importance = T,ntree = 1000)
varImpPlot(rf)

#Based on the visualization, smoker, age and bmi are the more significant, some more, some less. While choldren, 
#region and gender are evidently barely significant, which means they do not have a strong effect on the charges.

#We will use linear regression to compare the results with the random forest output.
children<-as.character(data$children)
model <-lm(charges ~ smoker+region+bmi+age+male+children+smoker, data)
summary(model)

# VIII. Ensemble prediction with Stacking
#To achieve a higher accuracy in prediction, we will combine different model predictions into one ensemble prediction.
#We will use stacking method to do so.
#Now we split the data into training and testing datasets
train <- createDataPartition(y = data$charges,p = 0.75,list = FALSE)
training <- data[train,]
testing <- data[-train,]
#Next we create repeated cross validation object 
fit <- trainControl(method = 'repeatedcv',number = 10, repeats = 5, summaryFunction=defaultSummary)
#We need to build an object to hold the list of algorithms
algorithmList <- c('lm','pls','rf', 'svmRadial')
#Training of sub models
models <- caretList(charges~., data=training, trControl=fit, methodList=algorithmList, preProcess = c("center","scale"))
## Warning in trControlCheck(x = trControl, y = target): trControl
## $savePredictions not 'all' or 'final'. Setting to 'final' so we can
## ensemble the models.
## Warning in trControlCheck(x = trControl, y = target): indexes not defined
## in trControl. Attempting to set them ourselves, so each model in the
## ensemble will have the same resampling indexes.
results <- resamples(models)
summary(results)

dotplot(results, metric = 'Rsquared')

#This demonstrates that random forest is the optimal model out of four, it is approached by SVM with a Radial Kernel.
#Correlation of predictions
modelCor(results)
##                  lm       pls        rf svmRadial
## lm        1.0000000 0.9974380 0.6040723 0.6646681
## pls       0.9974380 1.0000000 0.6070780 0.6654061
## rf        0.6040723 0.6070780 1.0000000 0.8074397
## svmRadial 0.6646681 0.6654061 0.8074397 1.0000000
# Some of the models show relatively low correlation between each other, which means that they have different
# prediction. Ensemble prediction is more beneficial when the models suggest different predictions.
#Combine predictions using GLM
stack.glm <- caretStack(models, method="glm", metric="RMSE", trControl=fit)
print(stack.glm)
